name: COURSE OVERVIEW
intro:
COURSE OVERVIEW

Pharmacists are healthcare professionals who are expert on drugs. Therefore, a pharmacist is specially trained to be knowledgeable in every aspect of drugs. The massive knowledge is multidisciplinary and it ranges from the properties and actions of drugs to the technology and science behind the production of a medicinal product, to the rational use of a drug for optimal therapeutic outcome in patients. Beside working on drug presciption, pharmacy graduates can also enter into the pharmaceutical industry where one can be involved in the research and development of drugs, clinical trials, pharmaceutical marketing and pharmaceutical sales. Trinity University of Asia College of Allied Health Sciences offers BS Pharmacy, a four-year degree program with innovative curriculum that provides students the opportunity to develop practice skills in one of the most prominent hospital institution in the country – St. Luke’s Medical Center.


 THE LEARNING PLACE

Our faculty incorporate active learning, simulated patient-care experiences and other strategies to facilitate the continued development and application of critical thinking and clinical skills with progressive and innovative facilities.


AFFILIATIONS

The BS Pharmacy Program has affiliations with a wide range of pharmacy practice settings where student pharmacists participate in experiential education throughout their academic program.

PROGRAM OUTCOMES

Our students consistently achieve success during and after they graduate from the program. We make sure that we guide you from enrollment to licensure examination to employment.


CAREERS

There is a wide variety of career opportunities for pharmacists in the areas of community pharmacy, hospitals or health systems, academia and many more!

name: THE DEAN
intro:
WELCOME TO TRINITY UNIVERSITY OF ASIA!

You are beginning a new chapter in your life here in TRINITY UNIVERSITY OF ASIA. It will be a challenging yet exciting and illuminating journey for you.

TRINITY UNIVERSITY OF ASIA is an AUTONOMOUS INSTITUTION. It is also a caring community of devoted alumni, faculty, staff, students and supporters of TRINITY UNIVERSITY OF ASIA. Once you join TRINITY UNIVERSITY OF ASIA, you will be a “TRINITIAN” now and ever. The distinctive literal health education at TRINITY UNIVERSITY OF ASIA will enable you to enjoy many facets of University Life. Open your mind and engage the whole around you. It falls to you to make the most of it.

I encourage you to set goals for your university life and work hard as academic excellence should not compromised. Explore, enjoy and fill your life with meaningful activities. We are here to work with you hand in hand to minimize your potentials and find out what you can do best. I expect you to exemplify the fine qualities of Health education of TRINITY UNIVERSITY OF ASIA and to be leaders who could contribute a better future for the world. Again, on behalf of the future front liners, WELCOME TO THE COLLEGE OF HEALTH ALLIED SCIENCES!!!

name: THE DEPARTMENT HEAD
intro:
A ROAD THAT UNFOLDED A PURPOSE

MA. ELEONOR CINCO SAN GABRIEL, PHARMD, RPH

My journey in becoming a Pharmacist in Academe has been a collection of unplanned and destiny-driven opportunities. I came to understand that God may have directed me towards this exceptional path with a purpose to prepare, train and mold student pharmacists as an authentic source of drug-related information and vital part of the healthcare community.

In my years of studying and early years of practice, I desired for more patient-oriented pharmacy practice. I worked directly with physicians and other healthcare professionals to ensure that the medications prescribed for patients contribute to the best possible health outcomes. As a Clinical Pharmacist, it is my responsibility to evaluate the appropriateness and effectiveness of the patient's medications. Indeed, it was a rewarding experience to be able to provide drug therapy counseling to patients. Fast forward to today, seeing how our TUA students raise the practice of pharmacy makes my career road a more meaningful, fulfilling and rewarding one. As a young pharmacist and educator, I am equipped with vast amount of energy and time hence, I am utilizing these to become an instrument in calibrating students' potentials and take part in the evolution of Pharmacy Practice to be fully recognized as an extraordinary profession in our country.

In behalf of the Faculty of Pharmacy Department, College of Allied Health Sciences, I welcome you to Trinity University of Asia! 100% Board Passing Rate! By enrolling in this program, you will learn how to develop and manufacture drugs for the diagnosis, treatment and prevention of diseases; how to manage pharmacies and how to assist patients with health and drug-related concerns. BS Pharmacy is also a preparatory course for Medicine. Indeed, there are diverse career opportunities waiting for you!

name: Course Overview
intro:
COURSE OVERVIEW

The Bachelor of Science in Radiologic Technology or BS RadTech is a four-year degree program designed to train students in operating various medical diagnostic and therapeutic equipment such as x-rays, CT scanners, MRIs, ultrasound machines, Medical Linear Accelerator(Medical Linac), Single Photon Emission Computed Tomographic machines (SPECT), Positron Emission Tomographic machines (PET), Digital Subtraction Angiographic machines(DSA) and 3D/4D medical imaging equipment and among other computer and web-based software programs. Students are also taught how to perform associated clerical duties, including scheduling and maintaining paperwork for office and clinical settings. They are required to attend an On the Job Training (OJT) in different tertiary hospitals doing clinical duty. Students are given the opportunity to apply their knowledge and skills in an actual work setting. To become a licensed radiologic technologist, a graduate of BS in Radiologic Technology needs to pass the Radiologic Technology Licensure Examination. The examination is conducted by the Board of Radiologic Technology under the supervision of the Professional Regulations Commission (PRC). Radiologic Technologists perform imaging and therapeutic examinations to patients. They are responsible for positioning patients on the lab equipment to ensure that a quality diagnostic image is produced. They work closely with radiologists in diagnosing these images for any possible disease, injury, and treatment

                                       

CAREER OPPORTUNITIES


Graduates of BS in Radiologic Technology may pursue a career path in different tertiary hospitals with a wide range of opportunities. Here are some of them:

1. X-ray Technologist

2. Ultrasound Technologist
3. CT-Scan Technologist (Computed Tomography)
4. MRI Technologist (Magnetic Resonance Imaging)
5. Mammography Technologist
6. Interventional Radiology Technologist
7. DSA Technologist (Digital Subtraction Angiography)
8. Radiation Therapy Technologist
9. PET Technologist (Positron Emission Tomography)
10.  Nuclear Medicine SPECT Technologist 

11. Industrial x-ray operator(nuclear power plant, airport x-ray surveillance machine operator)

12. Inspection officer(DOH-FDA-CDRRHR)
13. Medical dosimetrist 
14. Manager

15. Educator

name: COURSE OVERIEW
intro:
COURSE OVERVIEW

The Bachelor of Science in Respiratory Therapy is four- year program consist of  general health education and Professional courses. The first and second semesters of the fourth-year level is a one thousand six hundred (1,600) hours of clinical internship program in a CHED – DOH accredited training respiratory laboratory with rotational duties in different sections of one or more hospitals. Rotation in different clinical  areas include; pulmonary diagnostics, general respiratory care, adult intensive care unit, neonatal and pediatric critical care unit, sleep laboratory and pulmonary rehabilitation.

PROGRAM GOALS

The B.S. Respiratory Therapy program aims to produce Respiratory Therapist who are capable of:

1. Evaluating and assessing patients;

2. Planning and implementing respiratory therapy interventions based on guidelines and standards;

3. Participating in the promotion of the profession;

4. Valuing the importance of professional developing;

5. Appreciating the value of inter-professional communication and coordination with members of health care team

SPECIFIC PROFESSIONS/CAREERS/OCCUPATIONS FOR GRADUATES 

a. Clinician

b. Educator

c. Administrator

d. Product specialists

e. Researcher

f. Homecare Respiratory Therapist

g. Advocate

name: C2 - Post test
intro:
Instructions:
  1. Create a discussion by answering at least 3 topics below. One topic, one discussion. 
  2. Reply to at least 2 of your classmate's discussion.

Topic 1: Cyberbullying Message

While reviewing the email messages in your email account, you notice one that you interpret as cyberbullying. You do not recognize the sender of the email message, but you still take it seriously.  What are your next steps?

Topic 2: Unsolicited Friend Requests

You recently signed up for an account on Facebook. When you log in periodically, you find that people you do not know are requesting to be your friend. How should you respond?

Topic 3: Unexpected search engine
A class project requires that you conduct research on the web. After typing the web address for Google's home page and pressing the Enter key, your browser redirects you to a different search engine. What could be wrong?

Topic 4: Images do not appear
When you navigate to a webpage, you notice that no images are appearing. You successfully have viewed webpages with images in the past and are not sure why images suddenly are not appearing. What steps will you take to show the images?

Topic 5: Social Media Password
Your social media password has been saved on your computer for quite some time and the browser has been signing you in automatically. After deleting your browsing history and saved information from your browser, the online social network began prompting you again for your password, which you have forgotten. What are your next steps?

You will see a check across this activity once you completed the requirement.

Topic 1: Cyberbullying Message

While reviewing the email messages in your email account, you notice one that you interpret as cyberbullying. You do not recognize the sender of the email message, but you still take it seriously.  What are your next steps?

Topic 2: Unsolicited Friend Requests

You recently signed up for an account on Facebook. When you log in periodically, you find that people you do not know are requesting to be your friend. How should you respond?

Topic 3: Unexpected search engine
A class project requires that you conduct research on the web. After typing the web address for Google's home page and pressing the Enter key, your browser redirects you to a different search engine. What could be wrong?

Topic 4: Images do not appear
When you navigate to a webpage, you notice that no images are appearing. You successfully have viewed webpages with images in the past and are not sure why images suddenly are not appearing. What steps will you take to show the images?

Topic 5: Social Media Password
Your social media password has been saved on your computer for quite some time and the browser has been signing you in automatically. After deleting your browsing history and saved information from your browser, the online social network began prompting you again for your password, which you have forgotten. What are your next steps?

You will see a check across this activity once you completed the requirement.

name: Announcements (Please click this)
intro:
WELCOME, to our dear students.

This course starts on August 24 and will end on December 19, 2020.

In the course, we will adopt TLC (TUA Learning Cloud) as the Learning Management System (LMS) platform with, either synchronous or asynchronous eLearning modes depending on the preference of the class as a result of the Pre Survey to eLearning given to you during our first online meeting. As a requirement, you must secure a TUA email address.

The course utilizes flexible learning tools that allow students to interact with one another via video and audio discussions. Smartphones, tablets, laptops, or PC with these features can also be used to complete the activities. A worksheet material will be provided. Reading assignments will be posted on the TLC platform.


MAKE YOURSELF AN INSTRUMENT OF CHANGE

“Do nothing from selfish ambition or conceit, but in humility regard others as better than yourselves. Let each of you look not to your own interests, but to the interests of others. – (Phil 2:3,4) “

Treat your education as a personal “investment”. If you treat it as such, you must nurture it to increase its value. All investments come at a cost, not only the monetary cost (tuition) but in this case, also the time and effort you put into it. Getting the most out of your investment will only happen if the value that you get from it (revenue) is greater than the cost of getting it.

Dr. Marlon J. Gomez
Dean of Students

intro:

  7. Kaiwa 4.1 (Voice: 10, Content: 10, Gestures:10)Proper sounds or voice, Mastery of the flow of conversation, and Proper gestures.

name: How Do Historians Address the Reliability and Credibility of their Sources?
intro:
As what we've discussed in the class, historians are like detectives because they need to make sure that the information they deal and share to others is as accurate as possible. In this regards, they are expected to focus on six (6) factors to ensure that every historical information is reliable and credible. These are: 


1. Bias 

2. Accurate 

3. Prejudice 

4. Propaganda 

5. Exaggerated 

6. Fact or Opinion 


Explain how these factors contribute to the reliability and credibility of historical information.

name: Forum Participation
intro:
A forum is an asynchronous activity that you are required to accomplish for every lesson that we discuss. Our forum is an open space for you to be able to share to everyone your ideas and even opinions to others. After all, in our class, we learn from each other! 

You may even post your own questions in the forum in order to invite your fellow learners to a more engaging interaction.  The more interactive you are in the forum, the more chances that you have to receive high points in recitation. 

I expect that you will all be respectful of each other, but I ask you to review the following bulleted rules of engagement: 

  • Contributions in the group discussion will support the creation of an inclusive learning community;

  • Respect different viewpoints and experiences;

  • Be mindful of the impact the views and experiences you share may have on other learners

name: Verses to Familiarize, memorize, ponder upon, and to claim.
intro:
John 3: 16

For God, so LOVE the world that He gave His only begotten Son, that whoever believeth in Him should not perish, but have everlasting life.


John 1:12

But as many as received Him, to them He gave the power to become the sons of God, even to them that believe in His name.


1 John 5:11-13 (NIV) 11 And this is the testimony: God has given us eternal life, and this life is in His Son. 12 Whoever has the Son has life; whoever does not have the Son of God does not have life.


Concluding Affirmations

13 I write these things to you who believe in the name of the Son of God so that you may know that you have eternal life.


John 5:39 (New International Version)

39 You study the Scriptures diligently because you think that in them you have eternal life. These are the very Scriptures that testify about Me.




Matthew 22:37 The first and Greatest Commandment.

34 Hearing that Jesus had silenced the Sadducees, the Pharisees got together. 

35 One of them, an expert in the law, tested him with this question: 

36 “Teacher, which is the first and greatest commandment in the Law?”

37 Jesus replied:  Love the Lord your God with all your heart and with all your soul and with all your mind.’[c] 38 This is the first and greatest commandment. 

39 And the second is like it: ‘Love your neighbor as yourself.’[d] 40 All the Law and the Prophets hang on these two commandments.”


2 Timothy 3:16-17

    v. 16. All Scripture is given by inspiration of God and is profitable for doctrine, for reproof/reprimand, for correction,  for instruction in righteousness:

    v.17. That the man of God may be perfect, thoroughly furnished unto good works.

2 Peter 1:21

      For the prophecy came in old-time, not by the will of man: but holy men of God spake as they were moved by the Holy Ghost.


Verses to ponder and to claim

According to apostle Paul in Philippians 4:13, "I can do all things through Christ which strengtheneth me."
Isaiah 41:10 Don't you be afraid, for I am with you. Don't be dismayed, for I am your God. I will strengthen you. Yes, I will help you. Yes, I will uphold you with the right hand of my righteousness.

name: Discussion: Personality in Workplace
intro:
Instruction

  1. Post your response to the discussion prompt given below. This posting should be a minimum of one short paragraph and a maximum of two paragraphs. Word totals for this post should be in the 100–200-word range.
  2. After you have created your initial post, look over the discussion posts of your classmates and give at least two thoughtful responses to two different classmates (one per classmate). A response posting should be a minimum of one short paragraph. Word totals for these posts should be in the 75–100-word range. Whether you agree or disagree, explain why with supporting evidence and concepts from the readings or a related experience. Include a reference, link, or citation when appropriate. The goal of your response posts is to extend discussions already taking place or pose new possibilities or opinions not previously voiced. Your goal should be to motivate the group discussion and present a creative approach to the topic.

Discussion Prompt

Take an online personality test to measure the Big Five factors (you can search for “Big Five personality test,” or access an online Big Five Personalist test here). 

Which factors did you score highest in? Explain how your traits would help you excel in your current or previous jobs.

name: How Do Historians Address the Reliability and Credibility of their Sources?
intro:
As what we've discussed in the class, historians are like detectives because they need to make sure that the information they deal and share to others is as accurate as possible. In this regards, they are expected to focus on six (6) factors to ensure that every historical information is reliable and credible. These are: 


1. Bias 

2. Accurate 

3. Prejudice 

4. Propaganda 

5. Exaggerated 

6. Fact or Opinion 


Explain how these factors contribute to the reliability and credibility of historical information.

name: What to expect in CCSC class
intro: In this class, we will develop your will awareness and understanding of the similarities and differences between groups of people in the wider world beyond Asia. English-speaking cultural groups will be examined in terms of lifestyles, communication styles, and human behavior e.g. etiquette, beliefs, values, and social issues

name: Seatwork #2
intro:
Question: 

There's a quotation from Michael Crichton which states, "If you don't know history, then you don't know anything. You are a leaf that doesn't know it is part of the tree."

How can you relate the above quotation to our lesson today in connection to you as a student of TUA? Write your answer in 5 - 10 sentences.

name: Introduction to Biochemistry - Graded Recitation
intro:
Forum Rules

  • Write at least one answer to the question in the forum.
  • Replies to answers by your classmates are considered as one reply to the main question.
  • Make sure to be respectful of the answers or opinions of your classmates.
  • Do not type in ALL-CAPS.
  • Do not copy-paste without citing, it will be considered as Plagiarism.
  • If ever you are citing information, always add the reference you used.
  • FORUMS WILL CLOSE AT THE END OF THE CLASS PERIOD.

name: Expectations
intro: What are your expectations from this subject, your classmates, your instructor, and yourself?

name: Give your idea
intro: What is the Bible?

name: Discussion Forum
intro: Rule 1: Read the question and answer by posting 1 response. Rule 2: Be able to make a comment to the response of one of your classmates. Write your responses in 5 or more sentences.

name: Forum: God's Will
intro: In making an important decision, how do you know it is God's will?

name: Forum: Bible Preference
intro:
Christians would sometimes argue using one version of the Bible over the other.

Give your comment when you hear people say that their version is better?

name: Forum: Contemporary Issue
intro: In verse 27, "God created them, male and female." Some people say that this is an unfair statement. What contemporary issue do we face that made some people think that way? What is your comment about this issue?

name: Forum God's Blessings
intro: What does this quotation mean? God's blessings to us are not meant to end with us.

name: Forum: Better Person
intro: If there is a formula to becoming a better person what would you say is the secret to a healthy, successful, and happy life?

name: Forum: My life Mission
intro: What is your personal mission in life?

name: What is History?
intro:
History is the knowledge of and study of the past. It is the story of the past and a form of collective memory. History is the story of who we are, where we come from, and can potentially reveal where we are headed.

What about you? What do you think whenever you encounter the word history? Share your thoughts in this forum. To make it more interactive, you are encouraged to reply to your peers' insights. Please observe politeness and respect at all times.

name: Importance of History
intro:
History is important to study because it is essential for all of us in understanding ourselves and the world around us. There is a history of every field and topic, from medicine, to music, to art. To know and understand history is absolutely necessary, even though the results of historical study are not as visible, and less immediate.

Allows You To Comprehend More

1. Our World

History gives us a very clear picture of how the various aspects of society — such as technology, governmental systems, and even society as a whole — worked in the past so we understand how it came to work the way it is now.

 2. Society And Other People

Studying history allows us to observe and understand how people and societies behaved. For example, we are able to evaluate war, even when a nation is at peace, by looking back at previous events. History provides us with the data that is used to create laws, or theories about various aspects of society.

 3. Identity

 History can help provide us with a sense of identity. This is actually one of the main reasons that history is still taught in schools around the world. Historians have been able to learn about how countries, families, and groups were formed, and how they evolved and developed over time. When an individual takes it upon themselves to dive deep into their own family’s history, they can understand how their family interacted with larger historical change. Did family serve in major wars? Were they present for significant events?

 4. Present-Day Issues

History helps us to understand present-day issues by asking deeper questions as to why things are the way they are. Why did wars in Europe in the 20th century matter to countries around the world? How did Hitler gain and maintain power for as long as he had? How has this had an effect on shaping our world and our global political system today?

 5. The Process Of Change Over Time

 If we want to truly understand why something happened — in any area or field, such as one political party winning the last election vs the other, or a major change in the number of smokers — you need to look for factors that took place earlier. Only through the study of history can people really see and grasp the reasons behind these changes, and only through history can we understand what elements of an institution or a society continue regardless of continual change.


You Learn A Clear Lesson

1. Political Intelligence

 History can help us become better informed citizens. It shows us who we are as a collective group, and being informed of this is a key element in maintaining a democratic society. This knowledge helps people take an active role in the political forum through educated debates and by refining people’s core beliefs. Through knowledge of history, citizens can even change their old belief systems.

 2. History Teaches Morals And Values

 By looking at specific stories of individuals and situations, you can test your own morals and values. You can compare it to some real and difficult situations individuals have had to face in trying times. Looking to people who have faced and overcome adversity can be inspiring. You can study the great people of history who successfully worked through moral dilemmas, and also ordinary people who teach us lessons in courage, persistence and protest.

 3. Builds Better Citizenship

 The study of history is a non-negotiable aspect of better citizenship. This is one of the main reasons why it is taught as a part of school curricula. People that push for citizenship history (relationship between a citizen and the state) just want to promote a strong national identity and even national loyalty through the teaching of lessons of individual and collective success.

 4. Learn From The Past And Notice Clear Warning Signs

 We learn from past atrocities against groups of people; genocides, wars, and attacks. Through this collective suffering, we have learned to pay attention to the warning signs leading up to such atrocities. Society has been able to take these warning signs and fight against them when they see them in the present day. Knowing what events led up to these various wars helps us better influence our future.

 5. Gaining A Career Through History

 The skills that are acquired through learning about history, such as critical thinking, research, assessing information, etc., are all useful skills that are sought by employers. Many employers see these skills as being an asset in their employees and will hire those with history degrees in various roles and industries.

6. Personal Growth And Appreciation

 Understanding past events and how they impact the world today can bring about empathy and understanding for groups of people whose history may be different from the mainstream. You will also understand the suffering, joy, and chaos that were necessary for the present day to happen and appreciate all that you are able to benefit from past efforts today.


Develop And Refine Your Skills Through Studying History

1. Reading And Writing

 You can refine your reading skills by reading texts from a wide array of time periods. Language has changed and evolved over time and so has the way people write and express themselves. You can also refine your writing skills through learning to not just repeat what someone else said, but to analyze information from multiple sources and come up with your own conclusions. It’s two birds with one stone — better writing and critical thinking!

 2. Craft Your Own Opinions

 There are so many sources of information out in the world. Finding a decisive truth for many topics just doesn’t exist. What was a victory for one group was a great loss for another — you get to create your own opinions of these events.

 3. Decision-Making

 History gives us the opportunity to learn from others’ past mistakes. It helps us understand the many reasons why people may behave the way they do. As a result, it helps us become more impartial as decision-makers.

 4. How To Do Research

 In the study of history you will need to conduct research. This gives you the opportunity to look at two kinds of sources — primary (written at the time) and secondary sources (written about a time period, after the fact). This practice can teach you how to decipher between reliable and unreliable sources.

 5. Quantitative Analysis

 There are numbers and data to be learned from history. In terms of patterns: patterns in population, desertions during times of war, and even in environmental factors. These patterns that are found help clarify why things happened as they did.

 6. Qualitative Analysis

It’s incredibly important to learn to question the quality of the information and “history” you are learning. Keep these two questions in mind as you read through information: How do I know what I’m reading are facts and accurate information? Could they be the writer’s opinions?


What do you think are the other importance of history that was not mention in this discussion? Share your views in the forum below.

name: Geography and History
intro:
Geography is the study of places and the relationships between people and their environments. Geographers explore both the physical properties of Earth's surface and the human societies spread across it. Geography seeks to understand where things are found, why they are there, and how they develop and change over time. On the other hand, the historical record is inextricably linked to the geographic setting in which it developed." "History is concerned with understanding the temporal dimension of human experience (time and chronology). Geography is concerned with understanding the spatial dimension of human experience (space and place). This is where we see the intersection between the two. 


Combining History and Geography 

The relationship between history and geography is especially close because they represent two fundamental dimensions of the same phenomenon. History views human experience from the perspective of time, geography from the perspective of space. These dimensions of time and space are locked in an interactive feedback loop in which one dimension constantly affects the other.

According to Broek (1941), there are three assumptions to be considered in establishing the link between Geography and History: 

  • It is impossible to understand the present without understanding geography.
  • It is impossible to understand the present without understanding the past.
  • It is impossible to understand the past without understanding geography.
In other words, the rationale for history (studying the past to understand the present) requires knowing geography: today's geography and the geography of different places at different times in the past. Here are two examples of using the geographic perspective to understand history: 

1. The Philippines has been colonized by three countries (Spain, US, and Japan) over the years. If you will look at the location of the Philippines on the map, it is obvious that it is surrounded by water. This geographical location of the Philippines is one reason why it was very easy for invaders to enter our territory with ease. Although it was never the plan of Ferdinand Magellan to discover the Philippines in his journey, the chance of discovering our land apparently became easier and more probable due to the Philippines' archipelagic features. 

2. You may wonder why the Philippines is not a state of the US. Our geographical-proximal location is the reason why the US did not consider us a possible state. The Philippines is way too far from mainland US and travelling by boat or ship will take days during that time. Hawaii offered a different scenario to the US since proximity wise it is closer than the mainland and its location in the center of the Pacific serves as a perfect gateway to the US. 

Forum: 

Can you think of other relationship that exists between history and geography in the Philippine context? Provide events in the past to show the relationship between the two. Everybody is tasked to participate in the forum. You are encouraged to engage academic discussions with your peers to make this forum as interactive as possible. 

Reference/s: 

Jan O. M. Broek. (1941). The Relations between History and Geography. Pacific Historical Review, 10(3), 321–325. https://doi.org/10.2307/3633927

name: Forum Participation
intro:
A forum is an asynchronous activity that you are required to accomplish for every lesson that we discuss. Our forum is an open space for you to be able to share to everyone your ideas and even opinions to others. After all, in our class, we learn from each other! 

You may even post your own questions in the forum in order to invite your fellow learners to a more engaging interaction.  The more interactive you are in the forum, the more chances that you have to receive high points in recitation. 

I expect that you will all be respectful of each other, but I ask you to review the following bulleted rules of engagement: 

  • Contributions in the group discussion will support the creation of an inclusive learning community;

  • Respect different viewpoints and experiences;

  • Be mindful of the impact the views and experiences you share may have on other learners

name: How Do Historians Address the Reliability and Credibility of their Sources?
intro:
As what we've discussed in the class, historians are like detectives because they need to make sure that the information they deal and share to others is as accurate as possible. In this regards, they are expected to focus on six (6) factors to ensure that every historical information is reliable and credible. These are: 


1. Bias 

2. Accurate 

3. Prejudice 

4. Propaganda 

5. Exaggerated 

6. Fact or Opinion 


Explain how these factors contribute to the reliability and credibility of historical information.

name: What is History?
intro:
History is the knowledge of and study of the past. It is the story of the past and a form of collective memory. History is the story of who we are, where we come from, and can potentially reveal where we are headed.

What about you? What do you think whenever you encounter the word history? Share your thoughts in this forum. To make it more interactive, you are encouraged to reply to your peers' insights. Please observe politeness and respect at all times.

name: Importance of History
intro:
History is important to study because it is essential for all of us in understanding ourselves and the world around us. There is a history of every field and topic, from medicine, to music, to art. To know and understand history is absolutely necessary, even though the results of historical study are not as visible, and less immediate.

Allows You To Comprehend More

1. Our World

History gives us a very clear picture of how the various aspects of society — such as technology, governmental systems, and even society as a whole — worked in the past so we understand how it came to work the way it is now.

 2. Society And Other People

Studying history allows us to observe and understand how people and societies behaved. For example, we are able to evaluate war, even when a nation is at peace, by looking back at previous events. History provides us with the data that is used to create laws, or theories about various aspects of society.

 3. Identity

 History can help provide us with a sense of identity. This is actually one of the main reasons that history is still taught in schools around the world. Historians have been able to learn about how countries, families, and groups were formed, and how they evolved and developed over time. When an individual takes it upon themselves to dive deep into their own family’s history, they can understand how their family interacted with larger historical change. Did family serve in major wars? Were they present for significant events?

 4. Present-Day Issues

History helps us to understand present-day issues by asking deeper questions as to why things are the way they are. Why did wars in Europe in the 20th century matter to countries around the world? How did Hitler gain and maintain power for as long as he had? How has this had an effect on shaping our world and our global political system today?

 5. The Process Of Change Over Time

 If we want to truly understand why something happened — in any area or field, such as one political party winning the last election vs the other, or a major change in the number of smokers — you need to look for factors that took place earlier. Only through the study of history can people really see and grasp the reasons behind these changes, and only through history can we understand what elements of an institution or a society continue regardless of continual change.


You Learn A Clear Lesson

1. Political Intelligence

 History can help us become better informed citizens. It shows us who we are as a collective group, and being informed of this is a key element in maintaining a democratic society. This knowledge helps people take an active role in the political forum through educated debates and by refining people’s core beliefs. Through knowledge of history, citizens can even change their old belief systems.

 2. History Teaches Morals And Values

 By looking at specific stories of individuals and situations, you can test your own morals and values. You can compare it to some real and difficult situations individuals have had to face in trying times. Looking to people who have faced and overcome adversity can be inspiring. You can study the great people of history who successfully worked through moral dilemmas, and also ordinary people who teach us lessons in courage, persistence and protest.

 3. Builds Better Citizenship

 The study of history is a non-negotiable aspect of better citizenship. This is one of the main reasons why it is taught as a part of school curricula. People that push for citizenship history (relationship between a citizen and the state) just want to promote a strong national identity and even national loyalty through the teaching of lessons of individual and collective success.

 4. Learn From The Past And Notice Clear Warning Signs

 We learn from past atrocities against groups of people; genocides, wars, and attacks. Through this collective suffering, we have learned to pay attention to the warning signs leading up to such atrocities. Society has been able to take these warning signs and fight against them when they see them in the present day. Knowing what events led up to these various wars helps us better influence our future.

 5. Gaining A Career Through History

 The skills that are acquired through learning about history, such as critical thinking, research, assessing information, etc., are all useful skills that are sought by employers. Many employers see these skills as being an asset in their employees and will hire those with history degrees in various roles and industries.

6. Personal Growth And Appreciation

 Understanding past events and how they impact the world today can bring about empathy and understanding for groups of people whose history may be different from the mainstream. You will also understand the suffering, joy, and chaos that were necessary for the present day to happen and appreciate all that you are able to benefit from past efforts today.


Develop And Refine Your Skills Through Studying History

1. Reading And Writing

 You can refine your reading skills by reading texts from a wide array of time periods. Language has changed and evolved over time and so has the way people write and express themselves. You can also refine your writing skills through learning to not just repeat what someone else said, but to analyze information from multiple sources and come up with your own conclusions. It’s two birds with one stone — better writing and critical thinking!

 2. Craft Your Own Opinions

 There are so many sources of information out in the world. Finding a decisive truth for many topics just doesn’t exist. What was a victory for one group was a great loss for another — you get to create your own opinions of these events.

 3. Decision-Making

 History gives us the opportunity to learn from others’ past mistakes. It helps us understand the many reasons why people may behave the way they do. As a result, it helps us become more impartial as decision-makers.

 4. How To Do Research

 In the study of history you will need to conduct research. This gives you the opportunity to look at two kinds of sources — primary (written at the time) and secondary sources (written about a time period, after the fact). This practice can teach you how to decipher between reliable and unreliable sources.

 5. Quantitative Analysis

 There are numbers and data to be learned from history. In terms of patterns: patterns in population, desertions during times of war, and even in environmental factors. These patterns that are found help clarify why things happened as they did.

 6. Qualitative Analysis

It’s incredibly important to learn to question the quality of the information and “history” you are learning. Keep these two questions in mind as you read through information: How do I know what I’m reading are facts and accurate information? Could they be the writer’s opinions?


What do you think are the other importance of history that was not mention in this discussion? Share your views in the forum below.

name: Geography and History
intro:
Geography is the study of places and the relationships between people and their environments. Geographers explore both the physical properties of Earth's surface and the human societies spread across it. Geography seeks to understand where things are found, why they are there, and how they develop and change over time. On the other hand, the historical record is inextricably linked to the geographic setting in which it developed." "History is concerned with understanding the temporal dimension of human experience (time and chronology). Geography is concerned with understanding the spatial dimension of human experience (space and place). This is where we see the intersection between the two. 


Combining History and Geography 

The relationship between history and geography is especially close because they represent two fundamental dimensions of the same phenomenon. History views human experience from the perspective of time, geography from the perspective of space. These dimensions of time and space are locked in an interactive feedback loop in which one dimension constantly affects the other.

According to Broek (1941), there are three assumptions to be considered in establishing the link between Geography and History: 

  • It is impossible to understand the present without understanding geography.
  • It is impossible to understand the present without understanding the past.
  • It is impossible to understand the past without understanding geography.
In other words, the rationale for history (studying the past to understand the present) requires knowing geography: today's geography and the geography of different places at different times in the past. Here are two examples of using the geographic perspective to understand history: 

1. The Philippines has been colonized by three countries (Spain, US, and Japan) over the years. If you will look at the location of the Philippines on the map, it is obvious that it is surrounded by water. This geographical location of the Philippines is one reason why it was very easy for invaders to enter our territory with ease. Although it was never the plan of Ferdinand Magellan to discover the Philippines in his journey, the chance of discovering our land apparently became easier and more probable due to the Philippines' archipelagic features. 

2. You may wonder why the Philippines is not a state of the US. Our geographical-proximal location is the reason why the US did not consider us a possible state. The Philippines is way too far from mainland US and travelling by boat or ship will take days during that time. Hawaii offered a different scenario to the US since proximity wise it is closer than the mainland and its location in the center of the Pacific serves as a perfect gateway to the US. 

Forum: 

Can you think of other relationship that exists between history and geography in the Philippine context? Provide events in the past to show the relationship between the two. Everybody is tasked to participate in the forum. You are encouraged to engage academic discussions with your peers to make this forum as interactive as possible. 

Reference/s: 

Jan O. M. Broek. (1941). The Relations between History and Geography. Pacific Historical Review, 10(3), 321–325. https://doi.org/10.2307/3633927

name: Discussion Forum 1 - Introduction to Educational Psychology
intro:
GUIDE QUESTIONS

1. Upon watching the history of educational psychology, how does this field relevant in the practice of psychology?

2. What struck you the most in both the video and lecture? Why?

3. As aspiring psychology professional, to what extent are you interested to pursue this field? Explain why.


SPECIFIC INSTRUCTIONS

1. Answer the guide questions provided.

2. The answers must be brief yet concise. Kindly limit your answers to 200 words minimum and 400 words maximum.

3. After responding to the guide questions, provide a feedback to the answers of two other classmates.

4. In adding your responses, kindly indicate in the subject line DISCUSSION 1 FORUM SUBMISSION (LAST NAME, FIRST NAME).

5. This activity is worth 10 points.

5. Participation to this activity shall be part of the Class Participation domain in your Class Standing.

Society has been able to take these warning signs and fight against them when they see them in the present day. Knowing what events led up to these various wars helps us better influence our future.

 5. Gaining A Career Through History

 The skills that are acquired through learning about history, such as critical thinking, research, assessing information, etc., are all useful skills that are sought by employers. Many employers see these skills as being an asset in their employees and will hire those with history degrees in various roles and industries.

6. Personal Growth And Appreciation

 Understanding past events and how they impact the world today can bring about empathy and understanding for groups of people whose history may be different from the mainstream. You will also understand the suffering, joy, and chaos that were necessary for the present day to happen and appreciate all that you are able to benefit from past efforts today.


Develop And Refine Your Skills Through Studying History

1. Reading And Writing

 You can refine your reading skills by reading texts from a wide array of time periods. Language has changed and evolved over time and so has the way people write and express themselves. You can also refine your writing skills through learning to not just repeat what someone else said, but to analyze information from multiple sources and come up with your own conclusions. It’s two birds with one stone — better writing and critical thinking!

 2. Craft Your Own Opinions

 There are so many sources of information out in the world. Finding a decisive truth for many topics just doesn’t exist. What was a victory for one group was a great loss for another — you get to create your own opinions of these events.

 3. Decision-Making

 History gives us the opportunity to learn from others’ past mistakes. It helps us understand the many reasons why people may behave the way they do. As a result, it helps us become more impartial as decision-makers.

 4. How To Do Research

 In the study of history you will need to conduct research. This gives you the opportunity to look at two kinds of sources — primary (written at the time) and secondary sources (written about a time period, after the fact). This practice can teach you how to decipher between reliable and unreliable sources.

 5. Quantitative Analysis

 There are numbers and data to be learned from history. In terms of patterns: patterns in population, desertions during times of war, and even in environmental factors. These patterns that are found help clarify why things happened as they did.

 6. Qualitative Analysis

It’s incredibly important to learn to question the quality of the information and “history” you are learning. Keep these two questions in mind as you read through information: How do I know what I’m reading are facts and accurate information? Could they be the writer’s opinions?


What do you think are the other importance of history that was not mention in this discussion? Share your views in the forum below.

name: Geography and History
intro:
Geography is the study of places and the relationships between people and their environments. Geographers explore both the physical properties of Earth's surface and the human societies spread across it. Geography seeks to understand where things are found, why they are there, and how they develop and change over time. On the other hand, the historical record is inextricably linked to the geographic setting in which it developed." "History is concerned with understanding the temporal dimension of human experience (time and chronology). Geography is concerned with understanding the spatial dimension of human experience (space and place). This is where we see the intersection between the two. 


Combining History and Geography 

The relationship between history and geography is especially close because they represent two fundamental dimensions of the same phenomenon. History views human experience from the perspective of time, geography from the perspective of space. These dimensions of time and space are locked in an interactive feedback loop in which one dimension constantly affects the other.

According to Broek (1941), there are three assumptions to be considered in establishing the link between Geography and History: 

  • It is impossible to understand the present without understanding geography.
  • It is impossible to understand the present without understanding the past.
  • It is impossible to understand the past without understanding geography.
In other words, the rationale for history (studying the past to understand the present) requires knowing geography: today's geography and the geography of different places at different times in the past. Here are two examples of using the geographic perspective to understand history: 

1. The Philippines has been colonized by three countries (Spain, US, and Japan) over the years. If you will look at the location of the Philippines on the map, it is obvious that it is surrounded by water. This geographical location of the Philippines is one reason why it was very easy for invaders to enter our territory with ease. Although it was never the plan of Ferdinand Magellan to discover the Philippines in his journey, the chance of discovering our land apparently became easier and more probable due to the Philippines' archipelagic features. 

2. You may wonder why the Philippines is not a state of the US. Our geographical-proximal location is the reason why the US did not consider us a possible state. The Philippines is way too far from mainland US and travelling by boat or ship will take days during that time. Hawaii offered a different scenario to the US since proximity wise it is closer than the mainland and its location in the center of the Pacific serves as a perfect gateway to the US. 

Forum: 

Can you think of other relationship that exists between history and geography in the Philippine context? Provide events in the past to show the relationship between the two. Everybody is tasked to participate in the forum. You are encouraged to engage academic discussions with your peers to make this forum as interactive as possible. 

Reference/s: 

Jan O. M. Broek. (1941). The Relations between History and Geography. Pacific Historical Review, 10(3), 321–325. https://doi.org/10.2307/3633927

name: Discussion: Personality in Workplace
intro:
Instruction

  1. Post your response to the discussion prompt given below. This posting should be a minimum of one short paragraph and a maximum of two paragraphs. Word totals for this post should be in the 100–200-word range.
  2. After you have created your initial post, look over the discussion posts of your classmates and give at least two thoughtful responses to two different classmates (one per classmate). A response posting should be a minimum of one short paragraph. Word totals for these posts should be in the 75–100-word range. Whether you agree or disagree, explain why with supporting evidence and concepts from the readings or a related experience. Include a reference, link, or citation when appropriate. The goal of your response posts is to extend discussions already taking place or pose new possibilities or opinions not previously voiced. Your goal should be to motivate the group discussion and present a creative approach to the topic.

Discussion Prompt

Take an online personality test to measure the Big Five factors (you can search for “Big Five personality test,” or access an online Big Five Personalist test here). 

Which factors did you score highest in? Explain how your traits would help you excel in your current or previous jobs.

name: Forum Participation Guidelines
intro:
A forum is an asynchronous activity that you are required to accomplish for every lesson that we discuss. Our forum is an open space for you to be able to share to everyone your ideas and even opinions to others. After all, in our class, we learn from each other! 

You may even post your own questions in the forum in order to invite your fellow learners to a more engaging interaction.  The more interactive you are in the forum, the more chances that you have to receive high points in recitation. 

I expect that you will all be respectful of each other, but I ask you to review the following bulleted rules of engagement: 

  • Contributions in the group discussion will support the creation of an inclusive learning community;

  • Respect different viewpoints and experiences;

  • Be mindful of the impact the views and experiences you share may have on other learners

name: Stating the research question and alternative hypothesis
intro:
From 11 to 20 sample topics, choose only 3

1. Copy the topic

2. Identify the IV and DV

3. State in research problem in "What is the effect of ____ to ____ " form

4. State the alternative hypothesis in "If ____, then, _____" form


SAMPLE TOPICS:

1.     The effect displaying colorful food pictures inside the restaurant increases the customers buying tendency.

2.     The effect of tolerating one student to cheat during an examination influences the tendency of the other students to cheat.

3.     Allowing parents for a weekly visitation to drug rehabilitated patient to the patient’s recovery state.

4.     Sleeping before 10pm to student classroom engagement.

5.     The effect of doing group review to student’s score in math.

6.     The effect of taking down notes to student understanding of the concept in a lecture among Psychology students

 7.     Wearing white uniform increases student attitude towards attending their classes

 8.     Is 1 hour break better than 30 minutes in increasing workers’ productivity?

 9.     Is giving a verbal feedback better than giving a material reward in improving the eye contacts among children with autism?

 10.   Studying whether giving a “positive talk” by a coach during any game would give a better motivation to players rather  

         than  giving a “negative talk”.

11.  The effect of darkness to sleepiness.

12. Studying the effect of Online- classes to student motivation to accomplish home works.

13. The effect of corporal punishment in parental discipline to children’s tendency to explore.

14. Determining whether reading aloud while studying would help improve student ability to recall.

15. The effect of taking a 10 minute break every after 1 hr of reviewing to student comprehension level.

16. The effect of fasting to the cognitive functioning of the students.

17.  The effect of positive reinforcement to student engagement in extra-curricular activities.

18.  Studying if reading bible stories during bed time would enhance the children’s social behavior.

19.  The effect of watching Korea-novela to student attitude towards looking for an ideal partner.

20. The effect of listening to reggae music to one’s dispositional state.

name: Course Overview
intro: The course studies the philosophical, socio-cultural and psychological influences of social systems on individual behavior as well as on organizational activities and directions. In particular, it presents the social milieu of school organizations and individuals, the theoretical foundations of organizations, as well as the theories of human behavior in school organizations.

name: How Do Historians Address the Reliability and Credibility of their Sources?
intro:
As what we've discussed in the class, historians are like detectives because they need to make sure that the information they deal and share to others is as accurate as possible. In this regards, they are expected to focus on six (6) factors to ensure that every historical information is reliable and credible. These are: 


1. Bias 

2. Accurate 

3. Prejudice 

4. Propaganda 

5. Exaggerated 

6. Fact or Opinion 


Explain how these factors contribute to the reliability and credibility of historical information.

name: What is History?
intro:
History is the knowledge of and study of the past. It is the story of the past and a form of collective memory. History is the story of who we are, where we come from, and can potentially reveal where we are headed.

What about you? What do you think whenever you encounter the word history? Share your thoughts in this forum. To make it more interactive, you are encouraged to reply to your peers' insights. Please observe politeness and respect at all times.

name: Importance of History
intro:
History is important to study because it is essential for all of us in understanding ourselves and the world around us. There is a history of every field and topic, from medicine, to music, to art. To know and understand history is absolutely necessary, even though the results of historical study are not as visible, and less immediate.

Allows You To Comprehend More

1. Our World

History gives us a very clear picture of how the various aspects of society — such as technology, governmental systems, and even society as a whole — worked in the past so we understand how it came to work the way it is now.

 2. Society And Other People

Studying history allows us to observe and understand how people and societies behaved. For example, we are able to evaluate war, even when a nation is at peace, by looking back at previous events. History provides us with the data that is used to create laws, or theories about various aspects of society.

 3. Identity

 History can help provide us with a sense of identity. This is actually one of the main reasons that history is still taught in schools around the world. Historians have been able to learn about how countries, families, and groups were formed, and how they evolved and developed over time. When an individual takes it upon themselves to dive deep into their own family’s history, they can understand how their family interacted with larger historical change. Did family serve in major wars? Were they present for significant events?

 4. Present-Day Issues

History helps us to understand present-day issues by asking deeper questions as to why things are the way they are. Why did wars in Europe in the 20th century matter to countries around the world? How did Hitler gain and maintain power for as long as he had? How has this had an effect on shaping our world and our global political system today?

 5. The Process Of Change Over Time

 If we want to truly understand why something happened — in any area or field, such as one political party winning the last election vs the other, or a major change in the number of smokers — you need to look for factors that took place earlier. Only through the study of history can people really see and grasp the reasons behind these changes, and only through history can we understand what elements of an institution or a society continue regardless of continual change.


You Learn A Clear Lesson

1. Political Intelligence

 History can help us become better informed citizens. It shows us who we are as a collective group, and being informed of this is a key element in maintaining a democratic society. This knowledge helps people take an active role in the political forum through educated debates and by refining people’s core beliefs. Through knowledge of history, citizens can even change their old belief systems.

 2. History Teaches Morals And Values

 By looking at specific stories of individuals and situations, you can test your own morals and values. You can compare it to some real and difficult situations individuals have had to face in trying times. Looking to people who have faced and overcome adversity can be inspiring. You can study the great people of history who successfully worked through moral dilemmas, and also ordinary people who teach us lessons in courage, persistence and protest.

 3. Builds Better Citizenship

 The study of history is a non-negotiable aspect of better citizenship. This is one of the main reasons why it is taught as a part of school curricula. People that push for citizenship history (relationship between a citizen and the state) just want to promote a strong national identity and even national loyalty through the teaching of lessons of individual and collective success.

 4. Learn From The Past And Notice Clear Warning Signs

 We learn from past atrocities against groups of people; genocides, wars, and attacks. Through this collective suffering, we have learned to pay attention to the warning signs leading up to such atrocities. Society has been able to take these warning signs and fight against them when they see them in the present day. Knowing what events led up to these various wars helps us better influence our future.

 5. Gaining A Career Through History

 The skills that are acquired through learning about history, such as critical thinking, research, assessing information, etc., are all useful skills that are sought by employers. Many employers see these skills as being an asset in their employees and will hire those with history degrees in various roles and industries.

6. Personal Growth And Appreciation

 Understanding past events and how they impact the world today can bring about empathy and understanding for groups of people whose history may be different from the mainstream. You will also understand the suffering, joy, and chaos that were necessary for the present day to happen and appreciate all that you are able to benefit from past efforts today.


Develop And Refine Your Skills Through Studying History

1. Reading And Writing

 You can refine your reading skills by reading texts from a wide array of time periods. Language has changed and evolved over time and so has the way people write and express themselves. You can also refine your writing skills through learning to not just repeat what someone else said, but to analyze information from multiple sources and come up with your own conclusions. It’s two birds with one stone — better writing and critical thinking!

 2. Craft Your Own Opinions

 There are so many sources of information out in the world. Finding a decisive truth for many topics just doesn’t exist. What was a victory for one group was a great loss for another — you get to create your own opinions of these events.

 3. Decision-Making

 History gives us the opportunity to learn from others’ past mistakes. It helps us understand the many reasons why people may behave the way they do. As a result, it helps us become more impartial as decision-makers.

 4. How To Do Research

 In the study of history you will need to conduct research. This gives you the opportunity to look at two kinds of sources — primary (written at the time) and secondary sources (written about a time period, after the fact). This practice can teach you how to decipher between reliable and unreliable sources.

 5. Quantitative Analysis

 There are numbers and data to be learned from history. In terms of patterns: patterns in population, desertions during times of war, and even in environmental factors. These patterns that are found help clarify why things happened as they did.

 6. Qualitative Analysis

It’s incredibly important to learn to question the quality of the information and “history” you are learning. Keep these two questions in mind as you read through information: How do I know what I’m reading are facts and accurate information? Could they be the writer’s opinions?


What do you think are the other importance of history that was not mention in this discussion? Share your views in the forum below.

name: Geography and History
intro:
Geography is the study of places and the relationships between people and their environments. Geographers explore both the physical properties of Earth's surface and the human societies spread across it. Geography seeks to understand where things are found, why they are there, and how they develop and change over time. On the other hand, the historical record is inextricably linked to the geographic setting in which it developed." "History is concerned with understanding the temporal dimension of human experience (time and chronology). Geography is concerned with understanding the spatial dimension of human experience (space and place). This is where we see the intersection between the two. 


Combining History and Geography 

The relationship between history and geography is especially close because they represent two fundamental dimensions of the same phenomenon. History views human experience from the perspective of time, geography from the perspective of space. These dimensions of time and space are locked in an interactive feedback loop in which one dimension constantly affects the other.

According to Broek (1941), there are three assumptions to be considered in establishing the link between Geography and History: 

  • It is impossible to understand the present without understanding geography.
  • It is impossible to understand the present without understanding the past.
  • It is impossible to understand the past without understanding geography.
In other words, the rationale for history (studying the past to understand the present) requires knowing geography: today's geography and the geography of different places at different times in the past. Here are two examples of using the geographic perspective to understand history: 

1. The Philippines has been colonized by three countries (Spain, US, and Japan) over the years. If you will look at the location of the Philippines on the map, it is obvious that it is surrounded by water. This geographical location of the Philippines is one reason why it was very easy for invaders to enter our territory with ease. Although it was never the plan of Ferdinand Magellan to discover the Philippines in his journey, the chance of discovering our land apparently became easier and more probable due to the Philippines' archipelagic features. 

2. You may wonder why the Philippines is not a state of the US. Our geographical-proximal location is the reason why the US did not consider us a possible state. The Philippines is way too far from mainland US and travelling by boat or ship will take days during that time. Hawaii offered a different scenario to the US since proximity wise it is closer than the mainland and its location in the center of the Pacific serves as a perfect gateway to the US. 

Forum: 

Can you think of other relationship that exists between history and geography in the Philippine context? Provide events in the past to show the relationship between the two. Everybody is tasked to participate in the forum. You are encouraged to engage academic discussions with your peers to make this forum as interactive as possible. 

Reference/s: 

Jan O. M. Broek. (1941). The Relations between History and Geography. Pacific Historical Review, 10(3), 321–325. https://doi.org/10.2307/3633927

Guide Questions:

3. Consider the motivations of Pelisayo, Elisanda, and the townspeople. How does their treatment of the old man reflect what they value? What human truth does their treatment reveal? 

4. What is the relationship between old age and suffering in this story? 

5. What do the magical elements of the story reveal about the relationship  between old age and suffering in this story? 

6. How does the author draw on and transform "the Transformation of Arachne into a Spider?"

name: What is Culture?
intro:
Culture is the characteristics and knowledge of a particular group of people, encompassing language, religion, cuisine, social habits, music and arts.

Culture encompasses religion, food, what we wear, how we wear it, our language, marriage, music, what we believe is right or wrong, how we sit at the table, how we greet visitors, how we behave with loved ones, and a million other things. 

The word "culture" derives from a French term, which in turn derives from the Latin "colere," which means to tend to the earth and grow, or cultivation and nurture. "It shares its etymology with a number of other words related to actively fostering growth."


In this lesson, we are going to explore the culture of the Philippines through various dimensions with the hope of appreciating more what the country may offer to the world. 

What do you know about the Philippine culture? Share your thoughts about this in the forum below.

name: The Philippine Culture
intro:
The Philippines is one of the world’s largest archipelago nations. It is situated in Southeast Asia in the Western Pacific Ocean. Its islands are classified into three main geographical areas – Luzon, Visayas, and Mindanao. Because of its archipelagic nature, Philippines is a culturally diverse country. 

History and culture are two subjects intertwined in the establishment of individual identity. The traditions, values, and beliefs held by previous generations hold an indelible impact on how we view our place in the world. This is the reason why we cannot overlook Philippine culture when we explore the history of the country. 

As a Filipino or somebody who lives in the Philippines, you may have various accounts of cultural information about the nation. Yet, there are more things that we need to know about its culture besides what we already know. After all, the Philippines boasts its pluralistic cultural features as shown in its openness and resilience to different cultures. 

Visit this link in order to better understand the culture of the Philippines:  

https://www.britannica.com/place/Philippines/Cultural-life

What aspects of the Philippine culture makes you proud as a Filipino? If you are a foreigner, what certain cultural practices of the Filipinos are admirable? Share your views on these questions in the forum.

name: What should you do to preserve our culture?
intro:
"In your own little ways, how can you preserve the culture of the Philippines?" What aspect/s of our culture do you think should be preserved for future generations to appreciate?" 

Share your thoughts and insights in this forum.

name: Lesson 3: Kaiwa Itteyou!
intro:
For Today's Task, 4.1 Pair Activity: follow the steps below:
  1. Go to our gdrive link then access the folder for the activity Kaiwa itteyou!
  2. Find a partner to do the kaiwa(conversation) activity by simply listening to the audio file accompanied with the script in pdf format.
  3. Practice with your partner by doing the same script.
  4. For the activity please change some information from the original script such as (floor, object, amount, and country where the object is from)
  5. Once ready, create a zoom to record your conversation by following the sample.
  6. Upload your final video then label it with your name and your partner.  Take note:  For the final output please do not read the script and make sure that you will observe the following standards. 
  7. Kaiwa 4.1 (Voice: 10, Content: 10, Gestures:10)Proper sounds or voice, Mastery of the flow of conversation, and Proper gestures.

name: Course Overview
intro: The course studies the philosophical, socio-cultural and psychological influences of social systems on individual behavior as well as on organizational activities and directions. In particular, it presents the social milieu of school organizations and individuals, the theoretical foundations of organizations, as well as the theories of human behavior in school organizations.

name: Forum Participation
intro:
A forum is an asynchronous activity that you are required to accomplish for every lesson that we discuss. Our forum is an open space for you to be able to share to everyone your ideas and even opinions to others. After all, in our class, we learn from each other! 

You may even post your own questions in the forum in order to invite your fellow learners to a more engaging interaction.  The more interactive you are in the forum, the more chances that you have to receive high points in recitation. 

I expect that you will all be respectful of each other, but I ask you to review the following bulleted rules of engagement: 

  • Contributions in the group discussion will support the creation of an inclusive learning community;

  • Respect different viewpoints and experiences;

  • Be mindful of the impact the views and experiences you share may have on other learners

name: Discussion Forum 1
intro:
GUIDE QUESTIONS


1. Based on the three topics discussed, what insights have you gained in relation to its impact on studying the field of psychology?
2. What have you discovered when it comes to role of drugs in human's way of thinking, feeling, and behaving?
3. As a future psychology professional, what opportunities can you explore upon knowing these concepts and theories?

DIRECTIONS

1. Answer each question directly in the discussion forum.
2. Responses shall be in a minimum of 200 words and maximum of 500 words.
3. Just directly respond each question even without the question. Just properly put a number per answer.
4. Provide a feedback to your three (3) other classmates' responses.
5. This is equivalent to 15 points.

name: Discussion Forum on Antidepressants
intro:
GUIDE QUESTIONS


1. Based on the article, what have been your realizations on the impact of continuance and discontinuance of drugs in treating depressive disorders?

2. What are your key takeaways on the discussion?

3. As an aspiring psychologist/psychiatrist, what possible innovation shall you create in order to have a good impression about taking drugs, particularly in antidepressants?


SPECIFIC DIRECTIONS


1. Answer the guide questions provided.

2. Limit answers to 200 words minimum and 400 words maximum. 

3. Make answers brief and concise.

4. Add responses in the discussion forum using the file name DISCUSSION FORUM SUBMISSION (LAST NAME, FIRST NAME).

5. After posting your own answer, provide a comment to three (3) other classmates and focus your feedback on either you agree or disagree on the insights.

6. This activity is worth 15 points and shall count under your class participation grade.

name: Announcements
intro:
via GIPHY


Course Description:

This course allows the pre-service English teachers to explore the inextricable link between and among language, culture, and society and its implications to the development of English as a global language and the ways by which it is learned and taught. With this, they must demonstrate content knowledge and application of the lingua franca to cultural, societal, and even pedagogical development through a study of research-based principles in language and language teaching. Also, they must be able to gain insights of responsive learning environments in terms of language and community/society needs.


Course Learning Outcomes:
At the end of the course, the pre-service teachers should be able to:

A. demonstrate content knowledge and application of the relationship of language, culture, and society in the perspective of English language teaching;

B. apply research-based knowledge and principles of English language teaching and learning through case presentations and journal reviews; and

C. demonstrate an understanding of knowledge of language learning environments that respond to community contexts.

name: Announcements
intro:
via GIPHY


Course Description:

This course allows the pre-service English teachers to survey local and international basic education language programs and policies that account for issues and considerations relevant to the engagement of teachers in school settings. Moreover, it presents research-based content knowledge of language policies and programs across countries to exhibit clear understanding of the design, development, and dissemination of a language curriculum and to discuss how school policies i.e: language policies have shaped and influenced English language teaching in multicultural setting.


Course Learning Outcomes:

At the end of the course, the pre-service teachers should be able to:

A. demonstrate a research-based content knowledge and working awareness of the local and international language program and policies;

B. demonstrate knowledge in understanding of language policies and programs and their relevance to the engagement of teachers in school settings; and

C. demonstrate knowledge and understanding of school policies and procedures that shape and influence language teaching in multicultural setting.

intro: Hi. If there's anything you're confused about, feel free to ask your questions here. If you know the answer to your classmate's question, you may answer them. I appreciate those who apply what they learned and use critical thinking and analysis. Don't be afraid to give wrong answers because that's how we learn. This is a free space for everyone to ask academic questions. I'd advise you to please not be judgmental of your classmates. Help each other. Happy studying!

name: Seatwork #3 - Deadline: Oct. 24, 2022 at 12:00 NN
intro:
Questions

PATRIARCHS – 15 points

1. As mentioned in the video, who are the patriarchs?  Describe EACH OF THEM in 2 - 3 sentences. (10 points)

2. How did God show his love to people through the biblical patriarchs? Write your answer in 3 – 5 sentences. (5 points)

 

JUDGES – 15 Points

1. As described in the video, who are the biblical judges? (2 points)

2. Identify three ways why Israel’s total failure happened during the time of the judges. (3 points)

3. What is the cycle of sin during the time of judges? Can you see yourself in this cycle of sin? Explain your answer in 5 – 7 sentences. (10 points)

________________________________________

To Post your answer, you need to do the following: 

1. Click Finals - seatwork #1

2. Click "Add discussion topic"

3. Under "subject", write your Family Name and Given Name.

4. Under "message", write your answer. 

5. Click "post to forum"

name: GSTC WEBINAR PRESENTATION (NOV 7,21 2022)
intro:
