name: Reaction Paper
intro:
Read the article “Power and Conformity in Today’s Schools” written by Justin Saldana published in 2012. Your tasked is to write a reaction paper on the article by addressing the questions found below.  You can access the article here: https://ijhssnet.com/journals/Vol_3_No_1_January_2013/27.pdf

 

Guide questions:

1. How do you feel about what was written? Do you agree or disagree with the points raised?

2. Can you identify with any of the situations presented in the article? Do you have any experience related to any of the examples given?

3. Does the article prompt you to do something, or change any previous belief you might have? Or does it reinforce/support your existing stand on the topic?


Rubrics for scoring:

 

 

1

3

5

Content

Has no central idea and supporting details.

Central idea is vague and somewhat sketchy, lacks supporting detail

The work has a specific central idea which is clearly stated. The content is appropriate, it has concrete details that supports the central

idea.

Organization

Central point and flow of the essay is lost and lacks organization and

continuity.

Somewhat digresses from the central idea; ideas do not logically follow each other

Logically organized, well-structured, has a beginning, a body, and conclusion.

Grammar usage and mechanics

Many spelling, punctuation, and grammatical errors

Few spellings and punctuation errors, minor grammatical

errors

No spelling, punctuation, or grammatical errors

name: Critique Paper
intro:
Write a critical evaluation of the “No Child is Left Behind Policy.” The critique should be a balanced discussion and evaluation of the strengths, weakness and notable features of the policy. Remember to base the discussion on specific criteria. Good reviews also include other sources to support the evaluation. 

You will be graded in this activity using this rubric: 


https://www.cs.toronto.edu/~lczhang/csc290_20191/files/cr_rubric.pdf

name: Final Exam: Problem-Solution Essay
intro:
You are tasked to produce a 500-word essay that introduces a common problem that the educational sector is facing at this time. For Filipino students, you are encouraged to focus on the Philippine context, while Chinese students should focus on the Chinese context. Alongside, you are expected to propose a solution for this problem.


You will be graded in your final exam using this rubric: 


Focus and Central Purpose -       / 20%

 

o   Is the narrative well-paced?  Does the “problem” move evenly into the “solution?” 

o   Are the details about the “problem” and “solution” relevant and important? 

o   Does the essay have a clear and controlling central premise (problem)?

 

Organization -        / 30%

 

o   Is the problem presented in an engaging and interesting way that makes the importance of the issue clear? 

o   How well is the content of each paragraph organized to logically show how the solution fixes the problem?

o   Is the essay properly split into a “problem” and “solution” section?

 

Logical Solutions -        / 30%

 

o   Are each of the solutions presented reasonable and logically accurate, and do they have evidence-based content?

o   Are the solutions specific and concrete or generalized and insubstantial?

 

Conventions and Mechanics-          / 20%

 

o   The essay is free from spelling mistakes and other grammatical issues.

o   Does the word choice help build these outcomes through particular uses of vocabulary? 

 

Total Score:       /100

name: Enabling Task: Literary Analysis Paper
intro:
Your enabling task for the final period entails writing literary analyses for four (4) poems and one (1) play of your choice based on the list of literary selections in your course outline. You will choose the texts that you want to analyze. Below are the poems and plays: 

Contemporary Poetry

A.       “Mother to Son” by Langston Hughes

B.      “Siren Song” by Margaret Atwood

C.       “The Emperor’s New Sonnet” by Jose Garcia Villa

D.      “Litany” by Carolyn Creedon

E.       “The Ballad of the Lonely Masturbator” by Anne Sexton

F.       “Phenomenal Woman” by Maya Angelou

G.      “Vacation” by Rita Dove

H.      “Tulips” by Sylvia Plath

I.         “In the Hospital” by Chen Chen

J.         “Telephone Conversation” by Wole Soyinka


Contemporary Drama 

A.      “Cadaver” by Alberto Florentino

B.      “The Glass Menagerie” by Tennessee Williams

C.       “Speed-the-Plow” by David Mamet

 

Follow the guidelines provided in your previous material in writing your literary analyses. Your 5 literary analyses will be considered as your outputs for your class standing in the final period. Observe the following in writing your literary analyses: 


1. Use either Times New Romand or Book Antigua. The font size should be 12 and observe 1.5 spacing. Ensure that your margins are set to "Normal."

2. Provide catchy titles for your literary analyses. The titles can be based on theme of your discussion or the literary theory used in analyzing the texts. 

3. Your analyses should have at least 500 words and a maximum of 800 words. 

 4. All literary analyses should be submitted in the Drive on or before December 10, 2022. No extension will be given. 

5. You will be graded in these tasks using this rubric:


CRITERION

4

3

2

1

Introduction

The introduction is inviting, states the main topic and previews the structure of the paper.

The introduction clearly states the main topic and previews the structure of the paper, but is not particularly inviting to the reader.

The introduction states the main topic, but does not adequately preview the structure of the paper nor is it particularly inviting to the reader.

There is no clear introduction of the main topic or structure of the paper.

Support for Topic 

Relevant, telling, quality details give the reader important information that goes beyond the obvious or predictable.

Supporting details and information are relevant, but one key issue or portion of the analysis is unsupported.

Supporting details and information are relevant, but several key issues or portions of the analysis are unsupported.

Supporting details and information are typically unclear or not related to the topic.

Focus on Topic 

There is one clear, well-focused topic. Main idea stands out and is supported by detailed information.

Main idea is clear but the supporting information is general.

Main idea is somewhat clear but there is a need for more supporting information.

The main idea is not clear. There is a seemingly random collection of information.

Literary Lens Use

Seamlessly weaves literary lens into analysis of the novel. Use of lens is clear and accurate. Analysis enhances understanding of the novel.

Analysis is relevant to the lens and novel.

Use of lens is clear and accurate. Analysis enhances understanding of the novel.

Some effort to use lens for analysis of the novel but is not logical. Use of lens is unclear or inaccurate. Analysis somewhat enhances understanding of the novel.

Lens is merely mentioned or non existent. Use of lens is both unclear and inaccurate. Analysis does not enhance understanding of the novel.

Organization

The pacing is well-controlled. The writer knows when to slow down and elaborate, and when to pick up the pace and move on.

Details are placed in a logical order and the way they are presented effectively keeps the interest of the reader.

The pacing is generally well-controlled but the writer occasionally does not elaborate enough.

Details are placed in a logical order, but the way in which they are presented/introduced sometimes makes the writing less interesting.

The pacing is generally well-controlled but the writer sometimes repeats the same point over and over, or spends too much time on details that don't matter.

Some details are not in a logical or expected order, and this distracts the reader.

The pacing often feels awkward to the reader. The writer elaborates when there is little need, or leaves out necessary supporting information. Many details are not in a logical or expected order. There is little sense that the writing is organized.

Grammar & Spelling (Conventions)

Writer makes 2 or fewer errors in grammar or spelling that distract the reader from the content.

Writer makes 3-4 errors in grammar or spelling that distract the reader from the content.

Writer makes 5-6 errors in grammar or spelling that distract the reader from the content.

Writer makes more than 6 errors in grammar or spelling that distract the reader from the content.

intro:

name: COURSE OVERVIEW
intro:
COURSE OVERVIEW

Pharmacists are healthcare professionals who are expert on drugs. Therefore, a pharmacist is specially trained to be knowledgeable in every aspect of drugs. The massive knowledge is multidisciplinary and it ranges from the properties and actions of drugs to the technology and science behind the production of a medicinal product, to the rational use of a drug for optimal therapeutic outcome in patients. Beside working on drug presciption, pharmacy graduates can also enter into the pharmaceutical industry where one can be involved in the research and development of drugs, clinical trials, pharmaceutical marketing and pharmaceutical sales. Trinity University of Asia College of Allied Health Sciences offers BS Pharmacy, a four-year degree program with innovative curriculum that provides students the opportunity to develop practice skills in one of the most prominent hospital institution in the country – St. Luke’s Medical Center.


 THE LEARNING PLACE

Our faculty incorporate active learning, simulated patient-care experiences and other strategies to facilitate the continued development and application of critical thinking and clinical skills with progressive and innovative facilities.


AFFILIATIONS

The BS Pharmacy Program has affiliations with a wide range of pharmacy practice settings where student pharmacists participate in experiential education throughout their academic program.

PROGRAM OUTCOMES

Our students consistently achieve success during and after they graduate from the program. We make sure that we guide you from enrollment to licensure examination to employment.


CAREERS

There is a wide variety of career opportunities for pharmacists in the areas of community pharmacy, hospitals or health systems, academia and many more!

WELCOME TO TRINITY UNIVERSITY OF ASIA!

You are beginning a new chapter in your life here in TRINITY UNIVERSITY OF ASIA. It will be a challenging yet exciting and illuminating journey for you.

TRINITY UNIVERSITY OF ASIA is an AUTONOMOUS INSTITUTION. It is also a caring community of devoted alumni, faculty, staff, students and supporters of TRINITY UNIVERSITY OF ASIA. Once you join TRINITY UNIVERSITY OF ASIA, you will be a “TRINITIAN” now and ever. The distinctive literal health education at TRINITY UNIVERSITY OF ASIA will enable you to enjoy many facets of University Life. Open your mind and engage the whole around you. It falls to you to make the most of it.

I encourage you to set goals for your university life and work hard as academic excellence should not compromised. Explore, enjoy and fill your life with meaningful activities. We are here to work with you hand in hand to minimize your potentials and find out what you can do best. I expect you to exemplify the fine qualities of Health education of TRINITY UNIVERSITY OF ASIA and to be leaders who could contribute a better future for the world. Again, on behalf of the future front liners, WELCOME TO THE COLLEGE OF HEALTH ALLIED SCIENCES!!!

name: THE DEPARTMENT HEAD
intro:
A ROAD THAT UNFOLDED A PURPOSE

MA. ELEONOR CINCO SAN GABRIEL, PHARMD, RPH

My journey in becoming a Pharmacist in Academe has been a collection of unplanned and destiny-driven opportunities. I came to understand that God may have directed me towards this exceptional path with a purpose to prepare, train and mold student pharmacists as an authentic source of drug-related information and vital part of the healthcare community.

In my years of studying and early years of practice, I desired for more patient-oriented pharmacy practice. I worked directly with physicians and other healthcare professionals to ensure that the medications prescribed for patients contribute to the best possible health outcomes. As a Clinical Pharmacist, it is my responsibility to evaluate the appropriateness and effectiveness of the patient's medications. Indeed, it was a rewarding experience to be able to provide drug therapy counseling to patients. Fast forward to today, seeing how our TUA students raise the practice of pharmacy makes my career road a more meaningful, fulfilling and rewarding one. As a young pharmacist and educator, I am equipped with vast amount of energy and time hence, I am utilizing these to become an instrument in calibrating students' potentials and take part in the evolution of Pharmacy Practice to be fully recognized as an extraordinary profession in our country.

In behalf of the Faculty of Pharmacy Department, College of Allied Health Sciences, I welcome you to Trinity University of Asia! 100% Board Passing Rate! By enrolling in this program, you will learn how to develop and manufacture drugs for the diagnosis, treatment and prevention of diseases; how to manage pharmacies and how to assist patients with health and drug-related concerns. BS Pharmacy is also a preparatory course for Medicine. Indeed, there are diverse career opportunities waiting for you!

name: Course Overview
intro:
COURSE OVERVIEW

The Bachelor of Science in Radiologic Technology or BS RadTech is a four-year degree program designed to train students in operating various medical diagnostic and therapeutic equipment such as x-rays, CT scanners, MRIs, ultrasound machines, Medical Linear Accelerator(Medical Linac), Single Photon Emission Computed Tomographic machines (SPECT), Positron Emission Tomographic machines (PET), Digital Subtraction Angiographic machines(DSA) and 3D/4D medical imaging equipment and among other computer and web-based software programs. Students are also taught how to perform associated clerical duties, including scheduling and maintaining paperwork for office and clinical settings. They are required to attend an On the Job Training (OJT) in different tertiary hospitals doing clinical duty. Students are given the opportunity to apply their knowledge and skills in an actual work setting. To become a licensed radiologic technologist, a graduate of BS in Radiologic Technology needs to pass the Radiologic Technology Licensure Examination. The examination is conducted by the Board of Radiologic Technology under the supervision of the Professional Regulations Commission (PRC). Radiologic Technologists perform imaging and therapeutic examinations to patients. They are responsible for positioning patients on the lab equipment to ensure that a quality diagnostic image is produced. They work closely with radiologists in diagnosing these images for any possible disease, injury, and treatment

                                       

CAREER OPPORTUNITIES


Graduates of BS in Radiologic Technology may pursue a career path in different tertiary hospitals with a wide range of opportunities. Here are some of them:

1. X-ray Technologist

2. Ultrasound Technologist
3. CT-Scan Technologist (Computed Tomography)
4. MRI Technologist (Magnetic Resonance Imaging)
5. Mammography Technologist
6. Interventional Radiology Technologist
7. DSA Technologist (Digital Subtraction Angiography)
8. Radiation Therapy Technologist
9. PET Technologist (Positron Emission Tomography)
10.  Nuclear Medicine SPECT Technologist 

11. Industrial x-ray operator(nuclear power plant, airport x-ray surveillance machine operator)

12. Inspection officer(DOH-FDA-CDRRHR)
13. Medical dosimetrist 
14. Manager

15. Educator

name: COURSE OVERIEW
intro:
COURSE OVERVIEW

The Bachelor of Science in Respiratory Therapy is four- year program consist of  general health education and Professional courses. The first and second semesters of the fourth-year level is a one thousand six hundred (1,600) hours of clinical internship program in a CHED – DOH accredited training respiratory laboratory with rotational duties in different sections of one or more hospitals. Rotation in different clinical  areas include; pulmonary diagnostics, general respiratory care, adult intensive care unit, neonatal and pediatric critical care unit, sleep laboratory and pulmonary rehabilitation.

PROGRAM GOALS

The B.S. Respiratory Therapy program aims to produce Respiratory Therapist who are capable of:

1. Evaluating and assessing patients;

2. Planning and implementing respiratory therapy interventions based on guidelines and standards;

3. Participating in the promotion of the profession;

4. Valuing the importance of professional developing;

5. Appreciating the value of inter-professional communication and coordination with members of health care team

SPECIFIC PROFESSIONS/CAREERS/OCCUPATIONS FOR GRADUATES 

a. Clinician

b. Educator

c. Administrator

d. Product specialists

e. Researcher

f. Homecare Respiratory Therapist

g. Advocate
